                    <h3 class="head-sm fw-400" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">Water Quality</h3>
                    <p class="text-md mt-5" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">
                        In the summer of 2021, we drilled a network of eleven water
                        monitoring wells to establish baseline water quality, and these will remain in place, allowing us to continue to monitor water quality throughout the life of the mine. We also wanted to
                        monitor water direction, to determine whether our activities would impact Mackay Spring.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-md mt-5 mb-0" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">Our hydrologists have established that there will be no impact whatsoever. This will be confirmed by the EIS. This is because the groundwater is extremely deep, being 2,600 feet below the rim of the open pit, and is therefore protected by vast depths of rock.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    <div class="container communities">
        <div class="row">
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <img class="img-fluid w-100" src="images/water-usage-img.jpg" />
            </div>
            <div class="col-md-6">
                <div class="community-content">
                    <h4 class="head-lg text-red fw-400" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">04</h4>
                    <h3 class="head-sm fw-400" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">Water Usage</h3>
                    <p class="text-md mt-5" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">We are currently finishing the process design, but our current estimate is that our water requirement will be around 60 gallons per minute, all of which will be recycled. We expect to lose water only due to evaporation or ground absorption. Excess water will be required to reduce fugitive dust on the roads, a result of truck traffic. </p>
                    <p class="text-md mt-5 mb-0" data-aos="fade-up" data-aos-duration="2000">Part of the engineering and design process is securing an adequate water supply. As part of our ownership of the Empire patented claim, we are entitled to half of the water on Cliff Creek, which is currently dry. We have a monitoring station on Cliff Creek to measure the flow on a daily basis. Finding adequate water will not be easy, but we are legally permitted to establish a commercial well in order to secure the water supply we need.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
